{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:23:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:23:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1023"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1023"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.37,0.39,0.14,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113855"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1023"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6612"},{"type":"tags","id":"8751"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47272"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113855"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of progressive difficulty in speaking, with hoarseness and a change of tone in his voice. Over the same period, he has had difficulty with meals and notices an intermittent \u0027lump\u0027 sensation upon swallowing. His medical history includes nasal septum and inferior turbinate surgery six months ago, hip replacement, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His only medication is a statin for hyperlipidaemia. He quit smoking one year ago after a 50 pack-year history. He has limited exercise tolerance due to shortness of breath and hip pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Head and neck examination reveals no obvious masses or lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial diagnostic modality for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neck ultrasound","CT head and chest","Fibreoptic nasendoscopic evaluation of larynx","Barium swallow","C-spine x-ray"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s current symptoms, combined with a history of long-term smoking, a diagnosis of laryngeal malignancy is very likely and essential to exclude. Evaluation of the larynx by means of \u003Cstrong\u003Efibreoptic nasendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most practical and convenient way to visualise the upper airway. Guidelines recommend that individuals with dysphonia for \u0026gt; 2 weeks who have risk factors for laryngeal malignancy (e.g. history of smoking or prolonged, excessive alcohol use), or individuals with dysphonia for \u0026gt; 4 weeks without risk factors, undergo nasendoscopy. Given the patient\u0027s previous sinus surgery and lump on swallowing, observation of the nasal passage via fibreoptic nasendoscopy would also be useful. This is an outpatient procedure that does not require sedation, and it allows for direct visualisation as well as the potential for biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful tool that may be used to identify the site of dysphagia; however, it will not provide clear identification of the aetiology. A barium swallow is generally indicated to diagnose other pathologies, including (but not limited to) strictures, hiatal hernias, achalasia, reflux, and malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT head and chest \u003C/strong\u003Eprovides a wide range of information, including identification of neoplasms (e.g. bronchogenic carcinoma, oesophageal malignancy), infections, abnormal vasculature and airway abnormalities, and may be indicated further along the management pathway, depending on what is found on nasolaryngoscopy. For example, if he is found to have a paralysed vocal cord, a CT will be useful in looking for the underlying cause, but it is not the most appropriate first-line investigation. Imaging, including CT scan, is not recommended prior to visualising the larynx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the neck\u003C/strong\u003E is not a deep-penetrating modality and therefore only has use for superficial assessment of the neck. This allows for assessment of the thyroid, lymph nodes and carotid arteries. This may be useful for thyroid-related masses; however, given that there are no clinically palpable masses, a neck ultrasound is unlikely to be of diagnostic benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EC-spine radiograph\u003C/strong\u003E is typically performed to assess bony structures in the context of trauma to the head and neck. Soft tissue pathology (such as laryngeal carcinoma) would not be well visualised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibreoptic nasendoscopy is a first line investigation for individuals with dysphonia \u003E 2 weeks with risk factors for malignancy, or dysphonia \u003E 4 weeks without risk factors for malignancy.","Progressive dysphonia with dysphagia in an elderly smoker should raise suspicion for laryngeal malignancy."],"references":["Stachler RJ, Francis DO, Schwartz SR, Damask CC, Digoy GP, Krouse HJ, McCoy SJ, Ouellette DR, Patel RR, Reavis CCW, Smith LJ, Smith M, Strode SW, Woo P, Nnacheta LC. Clinical Practice Guideline: Hoarseness (Dysphonia) (Update). Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2018 Mar;158(1_suppl):S1-S42. doi: 10.1177/0194599817751030. Erratum in: Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2018 Aug;159(2):403. doi: 10.1177/0194599818766900. PMID: 29494321. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29494321/","Alvi S, Harsha P. Flexible Nasopharyngoscopy. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539740/","Selvanderan S, Wong S, Holloway R, Kuo P. Dysphagia: clinical evaluation and management. Intern Med J. 2021 Jul;51(7):1021-1027. doi: 10.1111/imj.15409. PMID: 34278699. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34278699/","Quested RA, Cooper LN. Hoarseness: An approach for the general practitioner. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2016;45:378-81. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/june/hoarseness-an-approach-for-the-general-practitione"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1023"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T08:22:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T08:23:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1023"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113855"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"sel